<statement>
  <p>[@@@@@@@@@]</p>
</statement>

<solution>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>There are enough spoons for each person to get one. There are more spoons than people.</p>
<p>Sample responses:</p>
<ul>
      <li>I pretended to give each person one spoon and there were some spoons left over.</li>
      <li>I matched up the spoons and people. There are more spoons.</li>
      <li>There are 6 spoons and 4 people. 6 is more than 4.</li>
    </ul>
  </solution>


<!-- ============================================================== 
   Notas profesor <prelude> (se pueden mostrar previo al enunciado)                      
===================================================================  -->
<prelude component="profesor"> 

  <!-- Tiempo recomendado -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="recommended-time-titulo"/></title>
    <p>10 minutos</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Introducción de la actividad -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="narrative-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>The purpose of this activity is for students to identify the group of objects that has more. This activity begins with a version of the Act it Out routine and builds on the student's work in the previous unit of answering <q>are there enough</q> questions. Students passed out, or matched up objects to determine if there were enough. Students build on this idea to help them determine which group has more objects. </p>
    <p>The context of family mealtimes that is introduced in this activity will be revisited throughout the unit. Acting it out gives students an opportunity to make sense of a context (MP1). As students share about the tools that they use when eating with their families, record and save their responses to refer to and add to in future lessons. Consider reading picture books about family mealtimes. Some suggestions include:</p>
    <p><em>Full, Full, Full of Love</em> by Trish Cooke <em>Bee-Bim Bop!</em> by Linda Sue Park <em>Yoko</em> by Rosemary Wells <em>The Little Red Hen (Makes a Pizza)</em> by Philomen Sturges <em>Rice &amp; Rocks</em> by Sandra L. Richards</p>
  </paragraphs>


  <!-- Materiales requeridos de la actividad -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="materials-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[@@@@@@@@@@@@@@]</p>
    <!-- si hay materiales, crear el siguiente archivo -mat.ptx y ponerlos ahí (y agregar también el archivo en la lista de materiales de la lección)-->
    <!-- <xi:include href="./act-cualTieneMas-mat.ptx"/>  -->
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Launch -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="launch-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Groups of 2</li>
      <li>Give each group of students access to connecting cubes and two-color counters.</li>
      <li>
        <q>Hemos aprendido sobre diferentes herramientas que usamos en nuestras casas y en nuestro salón de clase. ¿Qué tipo de herramientas usan en sus casas para comer?</q> (Spoons, forks, chopsticks, plates, bowls, napkins, cups, straws)
      </li>
      <li>30 seconds: quiet think time</li>
      <li>1 minute: partner discussion</li>
      <li>Share and record responses.</li>
      <li>
        <q>Usamos muchas herramientas diferentes para comer</q>
      </li>
      <li>Display and read the story.</li>
      <li>
        <q>¿De qué se trata la historia?</q> (A family eating dinner, Priya’s family, spoons for dinner)
      </li>
      <li>30 seconds: quiet think time</li>
      <li>Share responses.</li>
      <li>Read the story again.</li>
      <li>
        <q>¿Cómo pueden actuar esta historia?</q> (We can pretend we are sitting at the table and pretend to hand out spoons. We can use the cubes to show the people and the counters to show the spoons. We can draw a picture.)
      </li>
      <li>30 seconds: quiet think time</li>
      <li>1 minute: partner discussion</li>
      <li>Share responses.</li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>


  <!-- Instrucciones para el desarrollo de la actividad -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="instructions-teacher-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <q>Actúen la historia con su pareja</q>
      </li>
      <li>3 minutes: partner work time</li>
      <li>
        <q>¿Hay más personas o más cucharas? ¿Cómo lo saben?</q> (There are more spoons than people. Each person gets one spoon and then there are some more spoons.)
      </li>
      <li>2 minutes: partner work time</li>
      <li>Monitor for students who matched one spoon to each person to see if there were enough spoons and which there was more of.</li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>

</prelude>


